---
title: "Pattern Matching in Lateralus"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-06
abstract: We'll delve into the intricacies of pattern matching in Lateralus, exploring exhaustiveness checking, nested destructuring, guard clauses, and how match compiles to efficient code.

---

# Exhaustiveness Checking

One of the most important aspects of pattern matching is exhaustiveness checking. When a match fails, we want the compiler to ensure that all possible cases have been considered. In Lateralus, this is achieved through a combination of pattern syntax and compile-time checks.

fn greet(greeting: &str) -> String {
    match greeting {
        "hello" | "hi" => format!("Hello, {}", self.name),
        _ => "Generic Greeting".to_string(),
    }
}

In the above example, the `greet` function uses a single pattern branch with multiple alternatives. The `_` wildcard ensures that all other cases are matched, preventing exhaustiveness issues.

# Nested Destructuring

Lateralus also supports nested destructuring, allowing us to destructure complex data structures in a concise manner.

fn parse_args(args: [(&str, bool)]) -> (String, bool) {
    match args {
        [(arg, true)] => (arg.to_string(), false),
        [(_, false)] => ("Unknown Argument".to_string(), true),
    }
}

In this example, the `parse_args` function takes an array of tuples as input and returns a tuple containing two values. The `match` statement uses nested destructuring to extract the desired values from each tuple.

# Guard Clauses

Guard clauses provide a way to add additional logic to our match statements, enabling more nuanced behavior.

fn is_admin(user: User) -> bool {
    match user {
        User::Admin { role: Role::Admin } => true,
        _ => false,
    }
}

In this example, the `is_admin` function uses a guard clause to check if the `user` has an `Admin` role. If not, it immediately returns `false`.

